review_text:
I would use the poem "The Nailbiter" from this collection;
This poem is fun and silly, like most of Shel Silverstein's poems and describes a bad habit that they author has. It demonstrates repetition, rhyme, and a little bit of imagery.
This text could be used as a mentor text for students to write a poem about a habit they have that they wish they could change, however just like the poem, at the very end they have to come up with a reason that their habit is actually not so bad :"Before you star

So farewell hope and, with hope, farewell fear;
Farewell remorse.
I never know what kind of shit will go down between the time I finish reading and the time I finish reviewing. There's probably a way of integrating my newly acquired experience of being in an active shooter lockdown with this work, but as of now, I'm too tired to find it. The fact that this morning's events displaced my writing to a café while eating ice cream instead of my apartment while typing away will probably display itse

Something that struck me about this legendary accounting of the Trojan War is the cataloging of the soldiers. That is to say, whenever Achilles or Hector or some other hero strikes down a foe, Homer consistently bestows upon the slain man a flattering blurb of the following type;

Achilles threw his spear, killing Gregorios, who was a good dude and tall of stature. Then Hector leaped forward and slew Leto, who was a fine lad skilled with bow and spear.

